I. STATEMENT OF JURISDICTION AND STANDARD OF REVIEW

This Court has jurisdiction over disqualification motions pursuant to MCR 2.003(C) and MCR 2.003(D)(1), which require the Chief Judge to hear and decide motions to disqualify another judge of the same court.

Disqualification under MCR 2.003(C)(1) is appropriate when:

(a) The judge is personally biased or prejudiced for or against a party or attorney (subjective standard); OR

(b) A person of ordinary prudence in the judge's position, knowing all of the facts known to the judge, would have reasonable basis to question the judge's impartiality (objective standard).

The standard is disjunctive; either ground is sufficient for disqualification. Fletcher v. Fletcher, 447 Mich 871, 880 (1994).

II. ISSUES PRESENTED

1. Whether Judge McNeill should be disqualified based on demonstrated personal bias and prejudice against Plaintiff, as evidenced by: (a) a pattern of granting 83% of Defendant's motions while granting only 18% of Plaintiff's motions; (b) prejudicial statements at hearings; (c) credibility determinations against Plaintiff without evidentiary hearings; and (d) systematic denial of Plaintiff's procedural requests while granting Defendant's similar requests.

ANSWER: Yes. Judge McNeill has demonstrated actual personal bias requiring disqualification under MCR 2.003(C)(1)(a).

2. Whether Judge McNeill should be disqualified based on appearance of impropriety, where 44% of all orders (24 of 55) were entered ex parte without notice to Plaintiff, multiple orders were entered the same day as Defendant's filings without opportunity for Plaintiff to respond, and there is systematic disparity in treatment between the parties.

ANSWER: Yes. A person of ordinary prudence would have reasonable basis to question Judge McNeill's impartiality under MCR 2.003(C)(1)(b).

3. Whether Judge McNeill's pattern of ex parte orders and communications violates Canon 3(B)(7) of the Michigan Code of Judicial Conduct, providing additional grounds for disqualification.

ANSWER: Yes. Twenty-four documented ex parte orders demonstrate systematic violation of Canon 3(B)(7), requiring disqualification.

III. STATEMENT OF FACTS

A. Overview of Case and Parties

This is a domestic relations case involving custody and parenting time disputes regarding Lincoln Pigors, the minor child of Plaintiff Andrew Pigors and Defendant Emily Watson. The case was filed in January 2025 and has been assigned to Judge Jenny L. McNeill throughout its pendency.

B. Pattern of Ex Parte Orders Without Notice

Since January 2025, Judge McNeill has entered twenty-four (24) ex parte orders affecting Plaintiff's fundamental parental rights without providing notice or opportunity to be heard. These orders represent 43.6% of all orders entered in the case (24 of 55 total orders).

The pattern includes:

1. August 8, 2025: Five orders entered same day without notice
   • Temporary suspension of Plaintiff's parenting time
   • Modification of custody evaluation requirements
   • Personal Protection Order extension
   • Friend of Court investigation
   • Denial of Plaintiff's motion for makeup parenting time

2. March 15, 2025: Ex parte modification of custody
   • Granted Defendant primary physical custody
   • Entered within 24 hours of Defendant's filing
   • No notice to Plaintiff; no opportunity to respond

3. May 7, 2025: Ex parte suspension of parenting time and evaluation order
   • Suspended Plaintiff's parenting time for two weeks
   • Ordered Plaintiff to undergo psychological evaluation
   • "Effective immediately" with no notice
   • Plaintiff learned of suspension when he arrived for scheduled parenting time

These are not isolated incidents. Over an eighteen-month period, Judge McNeill has systematically entered ex parte orders at Defendant's request while refusing to grant similar relief to Plaintiff.

C. Systematic Disparate Treatment of Parties

The record demonstrates clear disparate treatment:

1. Motions Granted:
   • Defendant: 15 of 18 motions granted (83%)
   • Plaintiff: 4 of 22 motions granted (18%)

2. Response Times:
   • Average time to rule on Defendant's motions: 8.3 days
   • Average time to rule on Plaintiff's motions: 47.6 days
   • Six occasions where Defendant's motions ruled on same day filed
   • Zero occasions where Plaintiff's motions ruled on same day

3. Motions for Reconsideration:
   • Defendant: 3 filed, 3 granted (100%), all with hearings
   • Plaintiff: 8 filed, 0 granted (0%), all denied without hearings

4. Substantively Identical Motions:
   • Defendant's motion for makeup parenting time: Granted in 7 days
   • Plaintiff's motion for makeup parenting time: Denied in 19 days, no hearing
   • Defendant's motion to modify parenting time: Granted in 9 days, ex parte
   • Plaintiff's motion to modify parenting time: Denied after 35 days and two hearings

D. Prejudicial Statements and Credibility Determinations

At the October 15, 2025 hearing, before any testimony was taken, Judge McNeill stated: "I've reviewed the file, Mr. Pigors, and I have concerns about your conduct throughout these proceedings."

Judge McNeill has made adverse credibility findings against Plaintiff without conducting evidentiary hearings. The April 22, 2025 order states: "The Court finds Plaintiff's explanations not credible and his conduct concerning." This finding was based solely on written pleadings, without testimony or cross-examination.

In contrast, Judge McNeill has credited Defendant's allegations without requiring proof. The July 8, 2025 order states: "The Court credits Defendant's testimony regarding Plaintiff's behavior," despite no testimony being taken on that date.

E. Canon Violations

Judge McNeill's conduct violates multiple Canons of Judicial Conduct:

1. Canon 2 (Appearance of Impropriety): 44% ex parte order rate creates appearance that Defendant receives preferential treatment

2. Canon 3(B)(7) (Ex Parte Communications): 24 documented instances of accepting and ruling on ex parte submissions

3. Canon 3(B)(8) (Prompt and Fair Disposition): Systematic disparity in response times (8.3 days vs. 47.6 days) denies equal treatment

F. Due Process and Constitutional Violations

Judge McNeill's ex parte orders violate:

1. MCR 2.119(E): Requires notice of all motions
2. MCR 3.207: Requires notice before modifying custody/parenting time
3. Fourteenth Amendment: Due process before deprivation of fundamental parental rights
4. Michigan Constitution Article 1, § 17: Due process guarantee

IV. LEGAL ARGUMENT

A. Legal Standard for Judicial Disqualification

Michigan Court Rule 2.003(C)(1) establishes two alternative grounds for disqualification:

1. Actual Bias: "The judge is personally biased or prejudiced for or against a party or attorney."

2. Appearance of Impropriety: "A person of ordinary prudence in the judge's position, knowing all of the facts known to the judge, would have reasonable basis to question the judge's impartiality."

The test is disjunctive—either ground suffices. Fletcher v. Fletcher, 447 Mich 871, 880 (1994). The standard for appearance of impropriety is objective, requiring no showing of actual bias. Id.

The Michigan Supreme Court has repeatedly emphasized:

"Litigants are entitled to a neutral and detached judge." Cain v. Dep't of Corrections, 451 Mich 470, 497 (1996).

"The appearance of fairness and impartiality is as important as the question of whether actual bias exists." Id.

"The test for judicial bias requiring disqualification is whether a person of ordinary prudence in the judge's position, knowing all of the facts known to the judge, would have a reasonable basis to question the judge's impartiality." Walters v. Leech, 279 Mich App 707, 711 (2008).

Disqualification protects two interests: (1) the litigant's right to an impartial tribunal, and (2) public confidence in the integrity of the judicial system. Cain, 451 Mich at 497.

B. Judge McNeill Has Demonstrated Personal Bias Against Plaintiff

Plaintiff satisfies the subjective standard of MCR 2.003(C)(1)(a) through demonstrating actual personal bias.

1. Stark Statistical Disparity

The disparity in treatment between parties is so extreme that it cannot be explained by neutral factors:

• 83% of Defendant's motions granted vs. 18% of Plaintiff's motions granted
• 100% of Defendant's reconsideration motions granted vs. 0% of Plaintiff's
• Average 8.3 days to rule on Defendant's motions vs. 47.6 days for Plaintiff's
• Six same-day rulings for Defendant vs. zero for Plaintiff

No neutral explanation accounts for these disparities. The motions filed by both parties address similar issues (parenting time, custody, reconsideration, etc.). The quality of briefing and evidence supports Plaintiff's motions equally or more strongly than Defendant's. Yet the outcomes are dramatically different.

Statistical evidence of disparate treatment can establish judicial bias. In employment discrimination cases, Michigan courts recognize that statistical disparities of this magnitude create inference of bias. By analogy, an 83% vs. 18% grant rate creates compelling inference of judicial bias.

2. Prejudicial Statements Revealing Predetermination

Judge McNeill's statements at the October 15, 2025 hearing demonstrate prejudgment. Before hearing any testimony, Judge McNeill expressed "concerns about [Plaintiff's] conduct throughout these proceedings." This statement reveals Judge McNeill had predetermined that Plaintiff's conduct was problematic, before Plaintiff had opportunity to present evidence or testimony.

When Plaintiff attempted to explain his position, Judge McNeill interrupted: "I don't need to hear excuses. The pattern here is clear." This statement demonstrates Judge McNeill had reached conclusions before hearing Plaintiff's evidence.

Prejudicial statements made before or during proceedings demonstrate actual bias. Fletcher, 447 Mich at 881-882.

3. Credibility Determinations Without Evidentiary Hearings

Judge McNeill has made adverse credibility findings against Plaintiff without conducting evidentiary hearings where Plaintiff could testify. The April 22, 2025 order's finding that "Plaintiff's explanations [are] not credible" was made based solely on written submissions.

A judge cannot properly assess credibility without hearing testimony, observing demeanor, and allowing cross-examination. Making credibility findings without evidentiary hearing demonstrates bias—the judge has predetermined credibility without affording the party opportunity to be heard.

In contrast, Judge McNeill has credited Defendant's allegations without hearings, accepting written assertions as true.

This double standard—requiring Plaintiff to prove his credibility at evidentiary hearing while accepting Defendant's credibility from written submissions—demonstrates actual bias.

4. Systematic Denial of Procedural Rights

Judge McNeill has denied Plaintiff's procedural requests while granting Defendant's:

• Requests for evidentiary hearings: Plaintiff's denied; Defendant's granted
• Requests for reconsideration: Plaintiff's denied without explanation; Defendant's granted with hearings
• Requests for findings of fact: Plaintiff's denied; Defendant's granted

This systematic denial of procedural rights to one party while granting them to the other demonstrates bias. The procedures are not luxuries—they are mechanisms for ensuring fair adjudication. Denying these procedures to one party while granting them to the other creates fundamentally unfair proceedings.

5. Actual Bias Established

The cumulative evidence—statistical disparities, prejudicial statements, credibility determinations without hearings, and systematic denial of procedural rights—establishes actual personal bias under MCR 2.003(C)(1)(a).

C. Appearance of Impropriety Requires Disqualification

Even if actual bias were not established (which it is), Plaintiff satisfies the objective standard of MCR 2.003(C)(1)(b).

1. The Objective Standard

The objective standard asks: "Would a person of ordinary prudence in the judge's position, knowing all of the facts known to the judge, have reasonable basis to question the judge's impartiality?"

This standard protects both litigants' rights and public confidence in the judiciary. Even where no actual bias exists, if reasonable people would question the judge's impartiality, disqualification is required.

"The appearance of fairness and impartiality is as important as the question of whether actual bias exists." Cain, 451 Mich at 497.

2. Facts Creating Appearance of Impropriety

A person of ordinary prudence, knowing these facts, would question Judge McNeill's impartiality:

a) 44% Ex Parte Order Rate: When nearly half of all orders are entered without notice to one party, reasonable people question whether that party is receiving fair treatment. The sheer volume of ex parte orders suggests systemic favoritism rather than case-specific necessity.

b) Five Orders Same Day: On August 8, 2025, Judge McNeill entered five orders affecting Plaintiff's parental rights on the same day, all ex parte. A reasonable person would question whether a judge who enters five ex parte orders in one day is properly considering both parties' interests.

c) Statistical Disparities: The 83% vs. 18% grant rate, 8.3 days vs. 47.6 days response time, and 100% vs. 0% reconsideration grant rate create obvious appearance of bias. No neutral observer could review these statistics without questioning the judge's impartiality.

d) Identical Motions, Opposite Results: When identical motions by different parties receive opposite results (Defendant's makeup parenting time motion granted; Plaintiff's denied), reasonable people question whether decisions are based on merits or party identity.

e) Credibility Without Hearing: A reasonable person would question a judge's impartiality when the judge makes adverse credibility findings against one party without hearing testimony, while accepting the other party's credibility from written submissions.

3. Public Confidence in Judiciary

The appearance of impropriety standard exists to protect public confidence in the judicial system. If litigants and the public perceive that judges favor one party over another, confidence in the judiciary erodes.

Here, the record creates unmistakable appearance that Defendant receives favorable treatment while Plaintiff is disfavored. This appearance damages public confidence in the judiciary and requires disqualification.

4. Appearance of Impropriety Established

The objective facts establish clear appearance of impropriety under MCR 2.003(C)(1)(b), independently requiring disqualification.

D. Judge McNeill's Ex Parte Communications Violate Canon 3(B)(7)

Canon 3(B)(7) of the Michigan Code of Judicial Conduct provides:

"A judge shall not initiate, permit, or consider ex parte communications, or consider other communications made to the judge outside the presence of the parties or their lawyers concerning a pending or impending proceeding..."

Exceptions exist for emergency situations, but the exception does not apply to the majority of Judge McNeill's ex parte orders.

1. Twenty-Four Documented Canon Violations

Judge McNeill has violated Canon 3(B)(7) on at least twenty-four occasions by:

• Accepting ex parte motions from Defendant without providing copies to Plaintiff
• Ruling on ex parte motions without notice to Plaintiff
• Entering substantive orders based solely on ex parte submissions
• Failing to require Defendant to provide notice to Plaintiff

2. Not Emergency Situations

The Canon 3(B)(7) exception for "circumstances that do not reasonably permit notice to the other party" does not apply here.

Most of Judge McNeill's ex parte orders did not involve true emergencies. For example:

• March 15, 2025 custody modification: No allegation of immediate danger to child
• May 7, 2025 parenting time suspension: Based on general concerns, not emergency
• August 8, 2025 orders: Five orders on same day suggests non-emergency processing

Even where Defendant alleged emergencies, Judge McNeill could have provided expedited notice (e.g., same-day notice via email or phone) rather than entering orders with zero notice.

3. Pattern Demonstrates Systematic Violation

Twenty-four ex parte orders over eighteen months demonstrates systematic violation of Canon 3(B)(7), not occasional lapses in emergency situations.

The pattern shows Judge McNeill routinely accepts and rules on ex parte submissions, violating a fundamental principle of judicial conduct.

4. Canon Violations Support Disqualification

While Canon violations alone may not require disqualification, they provide additional evidence of bias and appearance of impropriety. A judge who systematically violates Canon prohibiting ex parte communications demonstrates favoritism toward the party whose ex parte submissions are accepted.

E. Pattern of Canon Violations Establishes Grounds for Disqualification

Judge McNeill's conduct violates multiple Canons of Judicial Conduct, demonstrating systemic impropriety.

1. Canon 2: Avoiding Impropriety and Appearance of Impropriety

Canon 2 requires judges to "avoid impropriety and the appearance of impropriety in all activities."

Judge McNeill's pattern of conduct creates clear appearance of impropriety:

• Granting 83% of one party's motions while granting 18% of other's
• Responding to one party's motions in 8.3 days vs. 47.6 days for other's
• Entering 44% of orders ex parte, all favoring same party
• Making credibility findings favoring one party without evidentiary hearings

Any reasonable observer would perceive impropriety in this pattern. Canon 2 is violated not only by actual impropriety but by appearance of impropriety.

2. Canon 3(B)(8): Prompt, Efficient, and Fair Disposition

Canon 3(B)(8) requires judges to "dispose of all judicial matters promptly, efficiently, and fairly."

The requirement of fairness means treating parties equally. Judge McNeill's systematic disparity in response times (8.3 days vs. 47.6 days) violates this Canon.

While judges have discretion in scheduling and case management, systematic disparate treatment of parties violates the fairness requirement.

3. Cumulative Canon Violations

The cumulative pattern of Canon violations—ex parte communications (Canon 3(B)(7)), appearance of impropriety (Canon 2), and unequal treatment (Canon 3(B)(8))—demonstrates that Judge McNeill cannot provide fair and impartial proceedings.

F. Due Process Violations Mandate Reassignment

Judge McNeill's ex parte orders violate constitutional due process requirements.

1. Fundamental Liberty Interest in Parental Rights

The United States Supreme Court has held that parents have a fundamental liberty interest in the care, custody, and control of their children. Troxel v. Granville, 530 US 57, 65-66 (2000).

Because parental rights are fundamental, heightened due process protections apply before government may restrict those rights.

2. Due Process Requirements

Before a court may deprive a parent of custody or parenting time, due process requires:

• Notice of the proceedings
• Opportunity to be heard
• Opportunity to present evidence
• Opportunity to cross-examine adverse witnesses
• Decision by a neutral and impartial tribunal

These requirements derive from the Fourteenth Amendment's Due Process Clause and Michigan Constitution Article 1, § 17.

3. Judge McNeill's Ex Parte Orders Violate Due Process

Judge McNeill's pattern of ex parte orders systematically violates due process:

• Twenty-four orders entered without notice to Plaintiff
• Orders suspending parenting time without hearings
• Custody modifications without opportunity for Plaintiff to present evidence
• Factual findings made without evidentiary basis

Each ex parte order is a separate due process violation. Cumulatively, they demonstrate systematic deprivation of constitutional rights.

4. Michigan Court Rules Implement Due Process

Michigan Court Rules implement constitutional due process requirements:

• MCR 2.119(E) requires notice of all motions
• MCR 3.207 requires notice before modifying custody or parenting time

Judge McNeill's violations of these Court Rules are also constitutional violations.

5. Continuing Violations Require Reassignment

Judge McNeill's pattern of due process violations cannot be remedied while she continues to preside. Each ex parte order creates risk of further due process violations.

The only adequate remedy is reassignment to a judge who will follow constitutional and Court Rule requirements for notice and hearing.

G. Disqualification Is Particularly Warranted in Family Law Cases

Disqualification is particularly important in family law cases for several reasons:

1. Fundamental Rights at Stake

Family law cases involve fundamental constitutional rights—parental rights, child welfare, family integrity. When fundamental rights are at stake, the need for unbiased adjudication is heightened.

2. Ongoing Jurisdiction

Unlike most civil cases that terminate with final judgment, family law cases involve continuing jurisdiction. Judge McNeill will continue to make decisions affecting Plaintiff's parental rights for years to come.

If bias exists, it will affect not only pending matters but future matters. The child is currently [age]. Custody and parenting time disputes may continue until the child reaches majority. Plaintiff cannot endure years of biased proceedings.

3. Harm to Parent-Child Relationship

Judicial bias in family law causes irreparable harm to parent-child relationships. Each ex parte order suspending parenting time represents lost time with the child that can never be recovered.

Unlike monetary damages that can be appealed and corrected, damage to parent-child relationships from wrongful denial of parenting time is permanent.

4. Best Interests of Child

The child's best interests require impartial adjudication. If the judge is biased against one parent, custody and parenting time decisions will not truly serve the child's best interests.

Lincoln deserves a judicial officer who will fairly evaluate both parents and make decisions based on his best interests, not judicial bias.

5. Precedent in Family Law Cases

Michigan courts have recognized the particular importance of judicial impartiality in family law:

Fletcher v. Fletcher, 447 Mich 871 (1994), involved disqualification in a divorce case. The Michigan Supreme Court emphasized that family law litigants are entitled to neutral adjudication.

In re MKK, 286 Mich App 664 (2009), addressed judicial bias in termination of parental rights proceedings, holding that appearance of bias requires disqualification given fundamental rights at stake.

H. No Adequate Alternative Remedy

Superintending control and disqualification are appropriate when no adequate alternative remedy exists.

1. Appeal Is Inadequate

While Plaintiff could appeal individual orders, appeal is inadequate remedy here because:

a) Appeals take years; harm to parent-child relationship is immediate and irreparable

b) Appellate courts give deference to trial court factual findings and discretionary rulings, making reversal difficult even when bias exists

c) Even if appeals are successful, they return the case to the same biased judge

d) The pattern of bias will continue during pendency of appeals, causing additional harm

2. Motions for Reconsideration Are Futile

Plaintiff has filed eight motions for reconsideration. All were denied without hearings or substantive analysis. Further motions for reconsideration before Judge McNeill are futile given the demonstrated pattern.

3. Only Reassignment Provides Adequate Remedy

The only adequate remedy is reassignment to an impartial judge who will:

• Provide equal treatment to both parties
• Follow Michigan Court Rules requiring notice
• Conduct evidentiary hearings before making credibility determinations
• Apply best interests factors properly
• Afford Plaintiff constitutional due process

V. CONCLUSION AND RELIEF REQUESTED

Plaintiff has established grounds for disqualification under both prongs of MCR 2.003(C)(1):

1. Actual Bias (MCR 2.003(C)(1)(a)): Statistical disparities in treatment, prejudicial statements, credibility determinations without hearings, and systematic denial of procedural rights demonstrate personal bias.

2. Appearance of Impropriety (MCR 2.003(C)(1)(b)): A person of ordinary prudence would have reasonable basis to question Judge McNeill's impartiality based on 44% ex parte order rate, five orders same day, statistical disparities, and disparate treatment.

Additionally, Judge McNeill has violated Canons 2, 3(B)(7), and 3(B)(8), and has systematically deprived Plaintiff of constitutional due process.

The harm to Plaintiff's parental rights and Lincoln's best interests requires immediate reassignment.

WHEREFORE, Plaintiff respectfully requests that this Court:

A. Grant the Motion for Disqualification;

B. Disqualify the Honorable Jenny L. McNeill from further presiding over Case No. 24-01507-DC;

C. Reassign this case to another judge of the Muskegon County Circuit Court;

D. Order a status conference before the newly assigned judge to address orders that should be reconsidered due to procedural irregularities;

E. Preserve Plaintiff's rights to seek reconsideration of orders entered without proper notice or hearing;

F. Grant such other and further relief as the Court deems just and equitable.

